posts.name: Itay Naumann
posts.cooked:
We, Orbit 1690, are going to have in 2024-06-23T18:00:00Z the second part of our online software sessions, where we are going to going to talk about: Our PoseTracker:

How we calculate odometry, position from apriltags, gamepiece position, detect skid, collision and what to do with both, and merge all of that information to get an accurate robotPose

2024 Shooting:

How we calculate the shot, shoot on the move and key principles to make all of it quicker and more accurate

And, lastly 2022 Shooting:

How the simulation worked and calculated, and how it ran in real time

We know it’s the second post we have about this topic but we saw more responses to the last session and we know that this is session will be cooler, on more complicated topics (which we’ve been asked about a ton) and we don’t want anyone who wants to watch it, but the other post didn’t attract him, miss it. Anyway, here is the link to register for it, if you want to ask a question related to the topics, you can ask it here If you’ve missed the last session and you want to watch it, it’s up on YouTube

posts.name: Yishai Levy
posts.cooked: Is your logger level 2 or level 3? If it’s level 2, a level 3 logging system has a great benefit over level 2, allowing to “go back in time” and record data you didn’t log in the match, as well as allowing for an easy way to incorporate simulations. More on the logging levels can be found in this conference.

posts.name: Itay Naumann
posts.cooked: Probably level 2, but we log enough information to understand everything we need

posts.name: Itay Naumann
posts.cooked: Sorry it took a while to upload , we had some technical difficulties, but here it is! Once again thank you for everyone who joined!
during the 2022 season what method did you use for your simulation?

posts.name: Itay Naumann
posts.cooked: It’s better explained in the video The simulation calculated for each pair of robot’s velocity and distance from the target it’s hood angle and ball velocity it needed to shot. We put the outputs in exel and graph a polynomial functions that best fitted the calculation.  With those functions the robot calculated the hood’s angle and ball’s velocity on the fly in the robot’s code each cycle

posts.name: Elliot S
posts.cooked: I was looking at some of your elims matches at worlds from 2022 and noticed you did not do much shooting on the move. Did you start having problems with it near the end of worlds?

posts.name: Itay Naumann
posts.cooked: We were defended by Project Y in the finals, and getting bumped while shooting is obviously not very helpful. So, we preferred to shoot from our safe zone or even up against the opponents’ safe zone to avoid getting bumped Also, against defense, chasing the balls wasn’t a good option so we were moving less in general

posts.name: sam liu
posts.cooked: Agree, Level 3 logging is not that perfect as it sounds.  The thing is, when the robot is behaving wiredly and there’s only 40 minutes to the next match, your best shot would be to catch the bug with your own experience, not the log.

posts.name: Yishai Levy
posts.cooked:
catrix:

your best shot would be to catch the bug with your own experience

Highly disagree. If you have experience reading logs, as well as doing replay, most of the times debugging through a log will actually be faster.

Keep in mind they mentioned a level 2 logging system, which still means they have a log to check for when debugging. It doesn’t contradict anything about the level 3 usage. It just means that if they forgot to log something, they’re out of luck.

Btw, not to mention how a level 3 logging system will be much better when calibrating stuff like the Kalman Filter between matches. You could replay the outputs with your new values and see how everything would react, instead of guessing.
i ment because the physical calculations cant be done with one nice equation. what method do you use to calculate the path of the ball. for example there is euler’s method

posts.name: Itay Naumann
posts.cooked:
We implemented an iterative simulation approach to model the ball’s trajectory Initial calculation:

We derived the initial forces based on the ball’s output velocity.

Iterative process, for each small time step (Δt):

Calculated acceleration, velocity, and position of the ball

Recalculated forces based on the new velocity

Repeated until the ball either reached the goal or missed

Trajectory evaluation:

Discarded missed shots

For successful shots, we calculated the associated cost

For further explanations you can see the session
